Sure, here is an example of how you can implement the tasks mentioned using CSS:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
<title>My CSS Practice</title>
<style>
    body {
        font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        margin: 0;
        padding: 0;
    }
    header {
        background-color: #333;
        padding: 10px;
        color: white;
        text-align: center;
    }
    .introduction {
        background-color: #f9f9f9;
        margin: 20px;
        padding: 10px;
    }
    .skills {
        padding: 10px;
    }
    .skills ul {
        list-style-type: none;
        padding: 0;
    }
    .skills li {
        border: 1px solid #333;
        padding: 5px;
        margin-bottom: 5px;
    }
    .contact {
        background-color: #f0f0f0;
        padding: 20px;
        text-align: center;
    }
    @media (max-width: 768px) {
        .introduction, .skills, .contact {
            margin: 10px;
            padding: 5px;
        }
    }
</style>
</head>
<body>
<header>
    <h1>John Doe</h1>
</header>

<section class="introduction">
    <h2>Introduction</h2>
    <p>Hello, I'm John Doe. I am a web developer based in XYZ.</p>
</section>

<section class="skills">
    <h2>Skills</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>HTML</li>
        <li>CSS</li>
        <li>JavaScript</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section class="contact">
    <h2>Contact Information</h2>
    <p>Email: johndoe@example.com</p>
    <p>Social Media: <a href="#">Twitter</a>, <a href="#">LinkedIn</a></p>
</section>

</body>
</html>
`
